Everywhere in the country-enclosed Bolivia, the memory of the stretch of coastline lost to Chile in a bloody conflict for resources in the 19th century is as alive as the desire to cross the Pacific again.
These hopes may be as strong as they have been for decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling by the International Court of Justice to be given on October 1 after five-year deliberations.
“Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and expects the result, of course, with a positive attitude,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Across the country, many Bolivians will follow the ICC’s ruling on large screens in the hope that the Hague court will decide in favour of Bolivia’s demand, which Chile, after decades of sporadic talks, is obliged to negotiate Bolivia’s sovereign access to the sea.
For Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president, who is facing a controversial battle for his re-election next year, the verdict on Monday is also at stake.
“We are on the verge of returning to the Pacific,” he pledged at the end of August.
However, some analysts consider it unlikely that the court will decide in favour of Bolivia, and believe that little would change as well.
The UN body, based in the Netherlands, is not authorized to allocate Chilean territory, and has determined that it will not decide on the outcome of possible talks.
According to Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law, the ICJ’s ruling has already been handed down six months after the final plea, concluding that the case was “not complicated”.
Far from supporting the Bolivian case, the past four years could also be a setback.
"The current Bolivian government has raised the issue of access to the sea," Zárate said.
It suggested that Morales' warlike rhetoric had stifled any remaining goodwill of Chile.
Bolivia and Chile will continue their talks at some point, but after these events, this will be extremely difficult.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, rejected the view that the court’s decision was abnormally fast.
On Monday, Bolivia has “an extraordinary opportunity to usher in a new era of relations with Chile” and an opportunity to “end the 139 years of mutually beneficial disputes,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents – used the issue of the sea as a political crutch.
