John Edward: Language skills are essential for world citizens
Scotland’s independent schools continue to stand out for academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with further outstanding exam results and is only underpinned by individual and joint achievements in the fields of sports, arts, music and other community ventures.
With more than 30,000 students from all over Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the highest possible level of care for their students and their parents.
Independent schools pursue the goal of preparing their students for further education and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as world citizens.
As an education sector that can design and put into practice a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and sought after in schools as electives.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart."
This is an impressive reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the current exam results of this year, we can see that languages with the highest pass rate are at the top of the rankings of independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned foreign languages scored A in the higher exams.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students in Mandarin scored A in the higher exams, while 72 percent of students studying German, 69 percent of students studying French, and 63 percent of students studying Spanish also scored A.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as an important knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now considered elective subjects as well as STEM subjects (science, engineering, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
According to a 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills, 17 percent of the reasons employers cited for the problems of filling vacancies were related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly essential when it comes to preparing young people for their future profession.
As more and more vacancies require languages, this knowledge is essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen profession, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage in the future through such a lifelong ability.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give multilingual people an edge over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage (15 percent).
For this reason, it is important for today’s children that we invest in language lessons now.
Children who speak multiple languages, especially languages from developing countries, will have better chances of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught in all schools.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK with a view to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Wherever your child’s interests lie, independent schools will always have a range of languages with appropriately specialized teachers to choose from.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares the children and equips them with the skills necessary for their success, whatever the future looks like.
At this point in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still of fundamental importance for the future of the country. Therefore, this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should actually be regarded as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
