North Korea rejects unilateral disarmament without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister said on Saturday before the United Nations that continued sanctions deepened its distrust of the United States and that under these circumstances the country would not give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the World Organization that North Korea "has taken essential measures last year out of good will," including stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and committing itself not to multiplying nuclear weapons and technologies.
"We don't see a response from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the US, there is no trust in our national security, and under these circumstances we will not unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
While Ri repeated trusted North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization approach where North Korea would be rewarded for successive steps, his statement seemed significant in that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization from the outset, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri pointed to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit meeting between an incumbent US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim had pledged to work towards “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump pledged guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is striving for an official end to the 1950-1953 Korean war, while the United States has said that Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington opposes demands for a relaxation of the stringent international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'first denuclearization' and increases the pressure from sanctions to achieve its goal by coercion, and is even against the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
“The assumption that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a brainstorming of people who don’t know anything about us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our distrust.”
Ri did not respond to plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. head of state had highlighted earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean head of state Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea were the other party on the denuclearization issue instead of the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to a standstill.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri’s speech was tremendously different from last year’s speech when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to use North Korea’s missiles to target the mainland of the United States after “evil president” Trump described Kim as a “missile man” on suicide missions.
This year, Trump, who threatened last year with the "complete destruction" of North Korea, praised Kim at the United Nations for his courage to take steps toward disarmament, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and the sanctions would have to remain in place until North Korea was denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for it: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months – it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council must reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “In any case, the enforcement of the Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously until we have reached complete, final and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously stepped up sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to financially dry out Pyongyang’s nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and subsequently said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was unsuccessful.
In July, he said on his departure from Pyongyang that progress had been made, only to be accused hours later by North Korea of making “gangster-like demands.”
North Korea pledged at a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle a rocket base and a nuclear complex if the United States took "corresponding measures."
He said Kim told him that the intended "corresponding measures" were security guarantees given by Trump in Singapore, as well as steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Learn to Sleep Enough in a Course
A new course at Harvard University ensures that all undergraduate students get more sleep this year, a measure against the spreading macho culture of keeping up with caffeine and learning all night long.
A scientist has found that students at the world’s leading university are often unnecessary when it comes to taking care of themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, and is in his opinion the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to launch the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about this now, in my last year?’
After all, no one had ever told her how important sleep is, and that surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
This year’s first-ever course taught students how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance and also improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the university’s health services, said the university chose to launch the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a range of interactive tasks.
In one section, students see the picture of a room in a dormitory and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the effects of lack of sleep on athletic performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, and cancer.
They are then encouraged to reflect on their daily routine by using a map of the university campus with interactive symbols.
“We know that it won’t change students’ behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know this, just as you have the right to know how smoking affects your health," Czeisler added.
The pride of “shushing a night shift” is still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-growing pressure on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep should be the “secret weapon” of all students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and weight gain could be avoided as sleep deprivation puts the brain into hunger mode so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who is studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having taken one of his courses in his first year at Harvard last year.
He said the course opened his eyes and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step, all postgraduate students will be asked to complete a similar study program before starting their studies at the competitive university.
According to Professor Czeisler's recommendation, students should set an alarm clock for bedtime and wake-up time, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emanating from electronic screens and LED lighting that can get the circadian rhythm off the beat, which leads to problems falling asleep.
