Syria is “ready” for the return of refugees, the foreign minister said.
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help for the reconstruction of the country devastated by the seven-year war.
In a speech to the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that the situation in the country is improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and safe thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government is rebuilding the territories destroyed by terrorists in order to restore normality.
All conditions are now in place for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that over 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian government welcomes assistance in rebuilding the devastated country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept conditional aid from countries that had supported the uprising.
Europe wins the Ryder Cup in Paris
Team Europa won the 2018 Ryder Cup and defeated Team USA with a 16.5 to 10.5 finish at Le Golf National near Paris.
The US has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the crown after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points it needed to defeat the US.
The American star Phil Mickelson, who had problems over much of the tournament, sank his tee on the 16th lane (Par 3) in the water and lost to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all his rounds and became one of 4 players who scored a 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
American Jordan Spieth was defeated 5:4 by the player with the lowest ranking in Team Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
The player with the world's best ranking, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 to 1 against the Englishman Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
Spaniard Sergio Garcia, veteran of eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player of all time with 25.5 career points.
“Normally I don’t cry, but today I couldn’t hold back.
It was a difficult year.
I am so grateful that Thomas chose me and believed in me.
I am so infinitely happy to win the cup back.
It's about the team and I'm happy to have made a contribution," said the emotional Garcia after the European victory.
He passes the torch on to his compatriot John Rahm, who won against American golf legend Tiger Woods on Sunday 2-1 in the individual matches.
"I'm so incredibly proud to have beaten Tiger Woods, whom I've been watching on TV since I was a child," Rahm said.
Woods lost all of his four matches in France and now has a Ryder Cup score of 13-21-3.
A strange statistic for one of the greatest players of all time, who has won 14 major titles and is only surpassed by Jack Nicklaus.
Team USA has been struggling to find the fairways all weekend, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who have performed well throughout the tournament.
American captain Jim Furyk said after a disappointing performance by his team: “I’m proud of the guys, they fought.
There was a time this morning when we had put pressure on Europe.
We didn't make anything out of it.
Hat off to Thomas.
He is a great captain.
All of his 12 players made a good performance.
We’re going to regroup, I’m going to talk to the PGA America and our Ryder Cup committee, and we’re going to look forward.
I love these 12 guys and I am proud to be their captain.
You have to take off your hat.
We were defeated.”
Red tide update: concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota are decreasing
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more volatile flowering conditions are recorded in the areas of the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier districts, indicating declining concentrations.
A red algae blossom extends over approximately 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of the Hillsborough district, but in fewer places compared to the previous week.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
In the past week, mean concentrations were reported in or off the coast of the Pinellas district, low to high concentrations off the coast of the Manatee district, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the Charlotte district, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the Lee district, and low concentrations in the Collier district.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier districts.
In northwest Florida, no new respiratory problems have been reported over the past week.
